(11012, 95, 'cs_content_blocks_1_cs_case_study_block_0_cs_case_study_structure_2_cs_second_column_content', 'Waggle had the vision to design an app that was immersive, incredibly user-friendly, and motivating for young students. This involved incorporating kid-friendly graphics (in Waggle’s case, flying pigs that are set free when students do well). There was also a requirement to build a dashboard for teachers to use in order to gauge the progress of their classroom and give them the insights they need to intervene quickly when a student is struggling.  Doing both things well required two minds to meet two equally significant end users: the students and the teachers. \r\n\r\nWaggle had considered building adaptivity on their own, but ultimately chose to partner with Knewton. Because Waggle’s reputation with schools was at stake, the level of trust between their team & Knewton’s needed to be high for the partnership to move forward.'),
