(11412, 390, 'cs_content_blocks_1_cs_case_study_block_0_cs_case_study_structure_1_cs_summary_content', 'Waggle is a teacher-administered classroom, homework, and supplemental practice tool that is easy to use, based in learning science, and rich in scaffolded, interactive content. Available in Math and English Language Arts, Waggle is powered by Knewton adaptive learning and fully aligned with National Common Core Standards.'),
(11413, 390, '_cs_content_blocks_1_cs_case_study_block_0_cs_case_study_structure_1_cs_summary_content', 'field_57e0cd4b7a656'),
(11414, 390, 'cs_content_blocks_1_cs_case_study_block_0_cs_case_study_structure_1_cs_summary_image', '203'),
(11415, 390, '_cs_content_blocks_1_cs_case_study_block_0_cs_case_study_structure_1_cs_summary_image', 'field_57e0cd7c7a657'),
(11416, 390, 'cs_content_blocks_1_cs_case_study_block_0_cs_case_study_structure_2_cs_challenges_heading', 'Challenges'),
(11417, 390, '_cs_content_blocks_1_cs_case_study_block_0_cs_case_study_structure_2_cs_challenges_heading', 'field_57e37782762f1'),
(11418, 390, 'cs_content_blocks_1_cs_case_study_block_0_cs_case_study_structure_2_cs_first_column_content', 'Triumph Learning, the creators of Waggle, was primarily a print publisher since 1999. Transitioning to application development with a focus on adaptivity was a resource risk that Waggle was willing to take,  albeit with reservations.\r\n\r\n<div class="quote">\r\n<p>“Triumph historically has been largely a print publisher and when we decided to create Waggle, we really wanted to make it unique and different.”</p>\r\n<div class="author-name">Rick Noble</div>\r\n<div class="author-detail">CEO Triumph Learning</div>\r\n</div>'),
(11419, 390, '_cs_content_blocks_1_cs_case_study_block_0_cs_case_study_structure_2_cs_first_column_content', 'field_57e125ef62712'),
(11420, 390, 'cs_content_blocks_1_cs_case_study_block_0_cs_case_study_structure_2_cs_second_column_content', 'Waggle had the vision to design an app that was immersive, incredibly user-friendly, and motivating for young students. This involved incorporating kid-friendly graphics (in Waggle’s case, flying pigs that are set free when students do well). There was also a requirement to build a dashboard for teachers to use in order to gauge the progress of their classroom and give them the insights they need to intervene quickly when a student is struggling.  Doing both things well required two minds to meet two equally significant end users: the students and the teachers. \r\n\r\nWaggle had considered building adaptivity on their own, but ultimately chose to partner with Knewton. Because Waggle’s reputation with schools was at stake, the level of trust between their team & Knewton’s needed to be high for the partnership to move forward.'),
